---
import BlogPost from '../../../../layouts/BlogPost.astro';
import { BLOG_POSTS } from '../../../../data/blog';

const meta = BLOG_POSTS.find((p) => p.slug === 'dscr-loans-real-estate-investors')!;

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'What is a DSCR loan in plain English?',
    answer:
      'A DSCR loan is a rental-property mortgage that qualifies on the property\'s rental cash flow instead of the borrower\'s personal income, tax returns, or W-2s. The lender divides the property\'s gross rent by its total monthly housing payment (PITIA) to get the DSCR ratio. A 1.0 ratio means rent exactly covers the mortgage payment.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What is the minimum DSCR ratio?',
    answer:
      'Most lenders, Clout included, will approve DSCR loans at a 1.0 ratio at standard pricing. Some files close below 1.0 with compensating factors — larger down payment, higher FICO, stronger reserves. Clout offers no-ratio DSCR on select programs at price for strong borrowers.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Can I use a DSCR loan on my primary residence?',
    answer:
      'No. DSCR loans are investment-property loans only. The property must be non-owner-occupied — a long-term rental, short-term rental, or second-home rental. Using a DSCR loan on a primary residence is occupancy fraud and a disqualifying condition.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What is the minimum FICO for a Clout DSCR loan?',
    answer:
      'Standard Clout DSCR programs require a 620 FICO minimum. Lower scores are sometimes possible with compensating factors — larger down payment, stronger DSCR ratio, or significant reserves. Pricing improves at 680, 720, and 740 FICO tiers.',
  },
];
---

<BlogPost
  slug={meta.slug}
  title={meta.title}
  description={meta.description}
  category={meta.category}
  datePublished={meta.datePublished}
  dateModified={meta.dateModified}
  lead="A DSCR loan is a rental-property mortgage that qualifies on the property's rental cash flow — not on the borrower's W-2 or tax returns. For real estate investors whose Schedule E understates their actual financial position, it's often the only loan that fits how the deal actually works."
  faqs={faqs}
>
  <h2>The underwriting logic nobody explains clearly</h2>
  <p>
    Conventional lenders underwrite the borrower. DSCR lenders underwrite the property. That's
    not a small distinction — it's a completely different framework. A Debt Service Coverage
    Ratio loan approves the deal based on whether the rent covers the mortgage payment, not on
    whether the borrower's tax returns show enough W-2 income. For investors who write off
    legally (as they should), this isn't a workaround. It's the product built for how a real
    estate investor actually operates.
  </p>

  <h2>Why your Schedule E hurts your conventional qualification</h2>
  <p>
    Here's the broken loop most investors hit: your CPA does excellent work, and that work
    kills your conventional financing. You depreciated the asset, deducted repairs, wrote off
    the property manager — and your Schedule E shows a fraction of the actual cash flow. A
    conventional underwriter uses that lower number for DTI. The property generates more than
    enough to cover the mortgage. The paper version of you doesn't. DSCR loans exist to bridge
    that exact gap.
  </p>

  <h2>How DSCR is calculated</h2>
  <p>
    DSCR = <strong>Gross rental income ÷ Monthly PITIA</strong> (principal, interest, taxes,
    insurance, and any HOA). A 1.0 ratio means rent exactly covers PITIA. Most lenders want
    1.10 to 1.25 at standard pricing. Clout's DSCR program approves at 1.0 at standard
    pricing and can go below with compensating factors.
  </p>
  <p>
    Worked example: a $2,500 monthly market rent on a property with $1,500 P&amp;I, $300 taxes,
    $150 insurance, and $0 HOA produces PITIA of $1,950 — so DSCR = $2,500 ÷ $1,950 = 1.28.
    That file prices at standard DSCR rates.
  </p>

  <h2>What Clout DSCR typically requires</h2>
  <div class="key-stats">
    <div><span class="k">Min FICO</span><span class="v">620</span></div>
    <div><span class="k">Max LTV (purchase)</span><span class="v">80%</span></div>
    <div><span class="k">Reserves</span><span class="v">3–12 months PITIA</span></div>
  </div>
  <p>
    LTV caps tighten on cash-out refinances (typically 70–75% maximum), and reserves scale up
    with property count and lower FICO bands. Exact program parameters are published inside
    <a href="/tpo-connect/">TPO Connect</a>; brokers can also run a scenario through the desk
    before submission.
  </p>

  <h2>What to do before you apply</h2>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Pull a rent schedule on the target property.</strong> If the market rent does not produce a DSCR of at least 1.0 at your expected price and down payment, the file will price up or decline.</li>
    <li><strong>Check your FICO.</strong> DSCR pricing is credit-sensitive. Most lenders publish tiers at 620 / 680 / 720 / 740.</li>
    <li><strong>Plan for 20–25% down.</strong> Most DSCR programs cap at 75–80% LTV.</li>
    <li><strong>Decide on vesting.</strong> LLC vesting is allowed at Clout; confirm before forming an entity solely for the transaction.</li>
    <li><strong>Document your reserves source.</strong> Liquid funds, not commingled with the down payment.</li>
    <li><strong>Don't try DSCR on a primary residence.</strong> Investment property only.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Frequently asked</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    {faqs.map((f) => (
      <details>
        <summary>{f.question}</summary>
        <div><p>{f.answer}</p></div>
      </details>
    ))}
  </div>

  <h2>Next steps</h2>
  <p>
    Investors can request a same-day eligibility read directly through <a href="/contact/">Clout</a>.
    Mortgage brokers placing wholesale DSCR files: see the <a href="/tpo-connect/">TPO Connect
    partner hub</a>. Related reading:
    <a href="/resources/blog/conventional-vs-dscr-investment-property/">Conventional vs DSCR for investment property</a> ·
    <a href="/resources/blog/cash-reserves-dscr-loan/">Cash reserves for DSCR loans</a> ·
    <a href="/resources/glossary/#dscr">DSCR in the glossary</a>.
  </p>
</BlogPost>
